  // Social: "14.5 million Americans still lack decent broadband, and most of them live in rural areas where cable and fiber never got built out. The good news: there are finally real options — Starlink, 5G home internet, fixed wireless, and more. Here's the no-BS guide to getting online when you live in the country."
  // Newsletter: "If you live in a rural area, you probably know the drill: the internet company says service is available, then shows up and tells you 'sorry, the line ends a mile down the road.' For years, rural Americans got stuck with slow DSL, overpriced satellite, or nothing at all. That's finally starting to change. Starlink, T-Mobile Home Internet, Verizon 5G Home, and a growing number of local fixed wireless providers are real options now — and many rural households can finally stream, work from home, and video chat without the buffering wheel of death. This guide walks through all the options, what they actually cost, what the speeds are really like in practice, and how to figure out which one makes sense for your address."
